772
00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:43.670
Lest zeal, now melted bythe windy breath

773
00:42:43.670 --> 00:42:47.130
Of soft petitions, pityand remorse,

774
00:42:47.130 --> 00:42:49.900
Cool and congeal again towhat it was.

775
00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:52.500
Why answer not the doublemajesties

776
00:42:52.500 --> 00:42:56.730
This friendly treaty ofour threaten'd town?

777
00:42:56.730 --> 00:43:01.630
Speak England first, thathath been forward first

778
00:43:01.630 --> 00:43:06.430
To speak unto this city:what say you?

779
00:43:06.430 --> 00:43:10.370
If that the Dauphin there,thy princely son,

780
00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:13.670
Can in this book of beautyread 'I love,'

781
00:43:13.670 --> 00:43:16.870
Then Anjou and fairTouraine, Maine, Poictiers,

782
00:43:16.870 --> 00:43:19.770
And all that we upon thisside the sea,

783
00:43:19.770 --> 00:43:21.870
Except this city now by usbesieged,

784
00:43:21.870 --> 00:43:24.270
Find liable to our crownand dignity,

785
00:43:24.270 --> 00:43:27.800
Shall gild her bridal bedand make her rich

786
00:43:27.800 --> 00:43:30.300
In titles, honours andpromotions,

787
00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:33.200
As she in beauty,education, blood,

788
00:43:33.200 --> 00:43:37.170
Holds hand with anyprincess of the world.

789
00:43:37.170 --> 00:43:43.470
What say'st thou, boy?look in the lady's face.

790
00:43:43.470 --> 00:43:47.470
I do, my lord; and in hereye I find a wonder,

791
00:43:47.470 --> 00:43:48.930
or a wondrous miracle,

792
00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:51.570
The shadow of myselfform'd in her eye:

793
00:43:51.570 --> 00:43:53.330
Which being but the shadowof your son,

794
00:43:53.330 --> 00:43:58.900
Becomes a sun and makesyour son a shadow:

795
00:44:00.130 --> 00:44:02.130
I do protest I never lovedmyself

796
00:44:02.130 --> 00:44:05.170
Till now infixed I beheldmyself

797
00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:10.130
Drawn in the flatteringtable of her eye.

798
00:44:11.800 --> 00:44:15.100
Drawn in the flatteringtable of her eye!

799
00:44:15.100 --> 00:44:18.300
Hang'd in the frowningwrinkle of her brow!

800
00:44:18.300 --> 00:44:21.930
And quarter'd in herheart! he doth espy

801
00:44:21.930 --> 00:44:27.430
Himself love's traitor:this is pity now,

802
00:44:27.430 --> 00:44:29.400
That hang'd and drawn andquartered, there should be

803
00:44:29.400 --> 00:44:34.200
In such a love so vile alout as he.

804
00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:37.800
My uncle's will in thisrespect is mine:

805
00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:40.430
If he see aught in youthat makes him like,

806
00:44:40.430 --> 00:44:43.200
That any thing he sees,which moves his liking,

807
00:44:43.200 --> 00:44:46.470
I can with ease translateit to my will;

808
00:44:46.470 --> 00:44:49.100
Or if you will, to speakmore properly,

809
00:44:49.100 --> 00:44:53.270
I will enforce it easilyto my love.

810
00:44:53.270 --> 00:44:55.270
Further I will not flatteryou, my lord,

811
00:44:55.270 --> 00:44:57.230
That all I see in you isworthy love,

812
00:44:57.230 --> 00:45:00.470
Than this; that nothing doI see in you,

813
00:45:00.470 --> 00:45:02.430
Though churlishthoughts themselves

814
00:45:02.430 --> 00:45:04.470
should be your judge,

815
00:45:04.470 --> 00:45:07.100
That I can find shouldmerit any hate.

816
00:45:10.430 --> 00:45:15.670
What say these young ones?What say you my niece?

817
00:45:15.670 --> 00:45:18.330
That she is bound inhonour still to do

818
00:45:18.330 --> 00:45:21.200
What you in wisdom stillvouchsafe to say.

819
00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:25.200
Speak then, prince Dauphin;can'st thou love this lady?

820
00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:27.430
Nay, ask me if I canrefrain from love;

821
00:45:27.430 --> 00:45:30.230
For I do love her mostunfeignedly.

822
00:45:30.230 --> 00:45:33.330
Then do I give Volquessen,Touraine, Maine,

823
00:45:33.330 --> 00:45:36.200
Poictiers and Anjou, thesefive provinces,

824
00:45:36.200 --> 00:45:39.200
With her to thee; and thisaddition more,

825
00:45:39.200 --> 00:45:43.630
Full thirty thousand marksof English coin.

826
00:45:43.630 --> 00:45:46.330
Philip of France, if thoube pleased withal,

827
00:45:46.330 --> 00:45:50.400
Command thy son anddaughter to join hands.

828
00:45:50.400 --> 00:45:54.730
It likes us well; youngprinces, close your hands.

829
00:45:54.730 --> 00:45:57.200
And your lips too; for Iam well assured

830
00:45:57.200 --> 00:45:59.770
That I did so when I wasfirst assured.

831
00:46:04.270 --> 00:46:08.630
Now, citizens of Angiers,ope your gates,

832
00:46:08.630 --> 00:46:11.230
Let in that amity whichyou have made;

833
00:46:11.230 --> 00:46:13.930
For at Saint Mary's chapelpresently

834
00:46:13.930 --> 00:46:17.370
The rites of marriageshall be solemnized.

835
00:46:19.930 --> 00:46:22.600
Is not the Lady Constancein this troop?

836
00:46:22.600 --> 00:46:25.070
I know she is not, forthis match made up

837
00:46:25.070 --> 00:46:27.230
Her presence would haveinterrupted much:

838
00:46:27.230 --> 00:46:29.130
