936
00:53:00.170 --> 00:53:01.730
Which harm within itselfso heinous is

937
00:53:01.730 --> 00:53:04.800
As it makes harmful allthat speak of it.

938
00:53:04.800 --> 00:53:07.700
I do beseech you, madam,be content.

939
00:53:07.700 --> 00:53:13.070
If thou, that bid'st me becontent, wert grim,

940
00:53:13.070 --> 00:53:16.700
Ugly and slanderous to thymother's womb,

941
00:53:16.700 --> 00:53:20.970
Full of unpleasing blotsand sightless stains,

942
00:53:20.970 --> 00:53:25.900
Lame, foolish, crooked,swart, prodigious,

943
00:53:25.900 --> 00:53:29.130
Patch'd with foul molesand eye-offending marks,

944
00:53:29.130 --> 00:53:33.070
I would not care, I thenwould be content,

945
00:53:33.070 --> 00:53:34.670
For then I should not lovethee, no, nor thou

946
00:53:34.670 --> 00:53:38.330
Become thy great birth nordeserve a crown.

947
00:53:38.330 --> 00:53:41.870
But thou art fair, and atthy birth, dear boy,

948
00:53:41.870 --> 00:53:48.470
Nature and Fortune join'dto make thee great:

949
00:53:48.470 --> 00:53:50.700
Of Nature's gifts thoumayst with lilies boast,

950
00:53:50.700 --> 00:53:56.270
And with the half-blownrose. But Fortune,

951
00:53:56.270 --> 00:54:00.630
O, She is corrupted,changed and won from thee;

952
00:54:00.630 --> 00:54:03.130
She adulterates hourlywith thine uncle John,

953
00:54:03.130 --> 00:54:06.630
And with her golden handhath pluck'd on France

954
00:54:06.630 --> 00:54:09.230
To tread down fair respectof sovereignty,

955
00:54:09.230 --> 00:54:14.470
And made his majesty thebawd to theirs.

956
00:54:14.470 --> 00:54:21.100
France is a bawd toFortune and King John,

957
00:54:21.100 --> 00:54:26.100
That strumpet Fortune,that usurping John!

958
00:54:26.100 --> 00:54:32.470
Tell me, thou fellow, isnot France forsworn?

959
00:54:32.470 --> 00:54:35.530
Envenom him with words, orget thee gone

960
00:54:35.530 --> 00:54:36.630
And leave those woes alonewhich I alone

961
00:54:36.630 --> 00:54:38.830
Am bound to under-bear.

962
00:54:38.830 --> 00:54:39.970
Pardon me, madam,

963
00:54:39.970 --> 00:54:43.430
I may not go without youto the kings.

964
00:54:44.700 --> 00:54:55.130
Thou mayst, thou shalt; Iwill not go with thee:

965
00:54:55.130 --> 00:54:58.800
I will instruct my sorrowsto be proud;

966
00:54:58.800 --> 00:55:03.170
For grief is proud andmakes his owner stoop.

967
00:55:05.070 --> 00:55:08.570
To me and to the state ofmy great grief

968
00:55:08.570 --> 00:55:13.700
Let kings assemble; for mygrief's so great

969
00:55:13.700 --> 00:55:17.230
That no supporter but thehuge firm earth

970
00:55:17.230 --> 00:55:24.170
Can hold it up: here I andsorrows sit;

971
00:55:24.170 --> 00:55:30.430
Here is my throne, bidkings come bow to it.

972
00:55:31.670 --> 00:55:34.500
'Tis true, fair daughter;and this blessed day

973
00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:36.570
