A rage whose heat haththis condition,

1240
01:11:41.730 --> 01:11:45.270
That nothing can allay,nothing but blood,

1241
01:11:45.270 --> 01:11:49.100
The blood, and dearest-valuedblood, of France.

1242
01:11:49.100 --> 01:11:53.300
Thy rage sham burn theeup, and thou shalt turn

1243
01:11:53.300 --> 01:11:58.330
To ashes, ere our bloodshall quench that fire:

1244
01:11:58.700 --> 01:12:02.800
Look to thyself, thou artin jeopardy.

1245
01:12:02.800 --> 01:12:07.170
No more than he thatthreats. To arms let's hie!

1246
01:12:11.770 --> 01:12:15.830
Now, by my life, this daygrows wondrous hot;

1247
01:12:15.830 --> 01:12:18.770
Some airy devil hovers inthe sky

1248
01:12:18.770 --> 01:12:24.570
And pours down mischief.Austria's head lie thou there,

1249
01:12:24.570 --> 01:12:26.930
While Philip breathes.

1250
01:12:27.430 --> 01:12:30.270
Hubert, keep this boy.Philip, make haste:

1251
01:12:30.270 --> 01:12:31.870
My mother is assailed inour tent,

1252
01:12:31.870 --> 01:12:32.770
And ta'en, I fear.

1253
01:12:32.770 --> 01:12:34.030
My lord, I rescued her;

1254
01:12:34.030 --> 01:12:35.830
Her highness is in safety,fear you not:

1255
01:12:35.830 --> 01:12:38.070
But on, my liege; for verylittle pains

1256
01:12:38.070 --> 01:12:41.070
Will bring this labour toan happy end.

1257
01:12:43.300 --> 01:12:45.230
So shall it be; yourgrace shall stay behind

1258
01:12:45.230 --> 01:12:47.430
So strongly guarded.

1259
01:12:47.430 --> 01:12:50.470
Cousin, look not sad:

1260
01:12:50.470 --> 01:12:52.670
Thy grandam loves thee;and thy uncle will

1261
01:12:52.670 --> 01:12:55.600
As dear be to thee as thyfather was.

1262
01:12:55.600 --> 01:12:58.500
O, this will make mymother die with grief!

1263
01:13:01.100 --> 01:13:02.830
Cousin, away for England! haste before:

1264
01:13:02.830 --> 01:13:05.200
And, ere our coming, seethou shake the bags

1265
01:13:05.200 --> 01:13:07.470
Of hoarding abbots;imprisoned angels

1266
01:13:07.470 --> 01:13:09.900
Set at liberty: the fatribs of peace

1267
01:13:09.900 --> 01:13:13.230
Must by the hungry now befed upon:

1268
01:13:13.230 --> 01:13:14.370
Use our commission in hisutmost force.

1269
01:13:14.370 --> 01:13:16.830
Bell, book, and candleshall not drive me back,

1270
01:13:16.830 --> 01:13:19.070
When gold and silver becksme to come on.

1271
01:13:19.070 --> 01:13:24.000
I leave your highness.Grandam, I will pray,

1272
01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:25.470
If ever I remember to beholy,

1273
01:13:25.470 --> 01:13:31.570
For your fair safety; so,I kiss your hand.

1274
01:13:34.100 --> 01:13:36.770
Farewell, gentle cousin.

1275
01:13:43.700 --> 01:13:46.770
Coz, farewell.

1276
01:13:46.770 --> 01:13:51.070
Come hither, littlekinsman; hark, a word.

1277
01:13:51.070 --> 01:13:53.070
Come hither, Hubert.

1278
01:14:03.530 --> 01:14:04.600
O my gentle Hubert,

1279
01:14:04.600 --> 01:14:07.900
We owe thee much! withinthis wall of flesh

1280
01:14:07.900 --> 01:14:10.500
There is a soul countsthee her creditor

1281
01:14:10.500 --> 01:14:13.870
And with advantage meansto pay thy love:

1282
01:14:13.870 --> 01:14:16.230
And my good friend, thyvoluntary oath

1283
01:14:16.230 --> 01:14:19.170
Lives in this bosom,dearly cherished.

1284
01:14:19.170 --> 01:14:20.830
Give me thy hand.

1285
01:14:25.470 --> 01:14:26.900
I had a thing to say,

1286
01:14:26.900 --> 01:14:31.430
But I will fit it withsome better tune.

1287
01:14:31.430 --> 01:14:34.230
By heaven, Hubert, I amalmost ashamed

1288
01:14:34.230 --> 01:14:36.630
To say what good respect Ihave of thee.

1289
01:14:36.630 --> 01:14:38.270
I am much bounden to yourmajesty.

1290
01:14:38.270 --> 01:14:40.700
Good friend, thou hast nocause to say so yet,

1291
01:14:40.700 --> 01:14:44.330
But thou shalt have; andcreep time ne'er so slow,

1292
01:14:44.330 --> 01:14:46.630
Yet it shall come from meto do thee good.

1293
01:14:50.170 --> 01:14:53.770
I had a thing to say, butlet it go:

1294
01:14:53.770 --> 01:14:56.370
The sun is in the heaven,and the proud day,

1295
01:14:56.370 --> 01:14:57.930
Attended with thepleasures of the world,

1296
01:14:57.930 --> 01:15:00.630
Is all too wanton and toofull of gawds

1297
01:15:00.630 --> 01:15:04.200
To give me audience: ifthe midnight bell

1298
01:15:04.200 --> 01:15:07.130
Did, with his iron tongueand brazen mouth,

1299
01:15:07.130 --> 01:15:10.930
Sound on into the drowsyrace of night;

1300
01:15:10.930 --> 01:15:13.300
If this same were achurchyard where we stand,

1301
01:15:13.300 --> 01:15:17.130
And thou possessed with athousand wrongs,

1302
01:15:17.130 --> 01:15:20.770
Or if that surly spirit,melancholy,

1303
01:15:20.770 --> 01:15:24.970
Had baked thy blood andmade it heavy-thick,

1304
01:15:24.970 --> 01:15:27.170
Which else runs ticklingup and down the veins,

1305
01:15:27.170 --> 01:15:29.970
Making that idiot,laughter, keep men's eyes

1306
01:15:29.970 --> 01:15:34.270
And strain their cheeks toidle merriment,

1307
01:15:34.270 --> 01:15:37.630
A passion hateful to mypurposes,

1308
01:15:37.630 --> 01:15:39.800
Or if that thou couldstsee me without eyes,

1309
01:15:39.800 --> 01:15:42.230
Hear me without thineears, and make reply

1310
01:15:42.230 --> 01:15:45.570
Without a tongue, usingconceit alone,

1311
01:15:45.570 --> 01:15:48.630
Without eyes, ears andharmful sound of words;

1312
01:15:48.630 --> 01:15:51.670
Then, in despite ofbrooded watchful day,

1313
01:15:51.670 --> 01:15:55.900
I would into thy bosompour my thoughts:

1314
01:15:57.800 --> 01:16:03.100
But, ah, I will not! yet Ilove thee well;

1315
01:16:03.100 --> 01:16:05.200
And, by my troth, I thinkthou lovest me well.

1316
01:16:05.200 --> 01:16:07.600
So well, that what you bidme undertake,

1317
01:16:07.600 --> 01:16:09.430
Though that my death wereadjunct to my act,

1318
01:16:09.430 --> 01:16:10.670
By heaven, I would do it.

1319
01:16:10.670 --> 01:16:13.130
Do not I know thouwouldst?

1320
01:16:13.130 --> 01:16:18.630
Good Hubert, Hubert,Hubert, throw thine eye

1321
01:16:18.630 --> 01:16:24.170
On yon young boy: I'lltell thee what, my friend,

1322
01:16:24.170 --> 01:16:26.830
He is a very serpent in myway;

1323
01:16:26.830 --> 01:16:29.100
And whereso'er this footof mine doth tread,

1324
01:16:29.100 --> 01:16:33.470
He lies before me: dostthou understand me?

1325
01:16:33.900 --> 01:16:35.170
Thou art his keeper.

1326
01:16:35.170 --> 01:16:36.400
And I'll keep him so,

1327
01:16:36.400 --> 01:16:38.100
That he shall not offendyour majesty.

1328
01:16:38.100 --> 01:16:38.930
Death.

1329
01:16:38.930 --> 01:16:39.670
My lord?

1330
01:16:39.670 --> 01:16:41.770
A grave.

1331
01:16:42.670 --> 01:16:45.130
He shall not live.

1332
01:16:45.870 --> 01:16:47.730
Enough.

1333
01:16:49.570 --> 01:16:57.530
I could be merry now.Hubert, I love thee;

1334
01:16:57.530 --> 01:17:01.030
Well, I'll not say what Iintend for thee:

1335
01:17:01.030 --> 01:17:04.170
Remember. Madam, fare youwell:

1336
01:17:04.170 --> 01:17:07.500
I'll send those powerso'er to your majesty.

1337
01:17:07.500 --> 01:17:10.670
My blessing go with thee!

1338
01:17:10.670 --> 01:17:13.300
Cousin, Away for England, go:

1339
01:17:13.300 --> 01:17:15.330
Hubert shall be your man,attend on you

1340
01:17:15.330 --> 01:17:21.400
With all true duty. Ontoward Calais, ho!

1341
01:17:32.770 --> 01:17:35.270
So, by a roaring tempeston the flood,

1342
01:17:35.270 --> 01:17:37.400
A whole armado ofconvicted sail

1343
01:17:37.400 --> 01:17:41.070
Is scatter'd and disjoin'dfrom fellowship.

1344
01:17:41.070 --> 01:17:46.070
Courage and comfort! allshall yet go well.

1345
01:17:46.070 --> 01:17:49.430
What can go well, when wehave run so ill?

1346
01:17:49.430 --> 01:17:52.270
Are we not beaten? Is notAngiers lost?

1347
01:17:52.270 --> 01:17:57.030
Arthur ta'en prisoner?divers dear friends slain?

1348
01:17:57.030 --> 01:17:59.530
And bloody England intoEngland gone,

1349
01:17:59.530 --> 01:18:03.100
O'erbearing interruption,spite of France?

1350
01:18:03.100 --> 01:18:06.530
What he hath won, thathath he fortified:

1351
01:18:06.530 --> 01:18:09.070
So hot a speed with suchadvice disposed,

1352
01:18:09.070 --> 01:18:11.830
Such temperate order in sofierce a cause,

1353
01:18:11.830 --> 01:18:15.270
Doth want example: whohath read or heard

1354
01:18:15.270 --> 01:18:16.500
Of any kindred action liketo this?

1355
01:18:16.500 --> 01:18:18.470
Well could I bear thatEngland had this praise,

1356
01:18:18.470 --> 01:18:24.170
So we could find somepattern of our shame.

1357
01:18:24.170 --> 01:18:29.830
Look, who comes here! agrave unto a soul;

1358
01:18:29.830 --> 01:18:32.170
Holding the eternal spiritagainst her will,

1359
01:18:32.170 --> 01:18:37.470
In the vile prison ofafflicted breath.

1360
01:18:37.470 --> 01:18:40.230
I prithee, lady, go awaywith me.

1361
01:18:40.230 --> 01:18:45.870
Lo, now I now see theissue of your peace.

1362
01:18:45.870 --> 01:18:48.100
Patience, good lady!comfort, gentle Constance!

1363
01:18:48.100 --> 01:18:52.230
No, I defy all counsel,all redress,

1364
01:18:52.230 --> 01:18:56.330
Save that which ends allcounsel, true redress,

1365
01:18:56.330 --> 01:19:04.170
Death, death; O amiablelovely death!

1366
01:19:04.170 --> 01:19:10.870
Thou odouriferous stench!sound rottenness!

1367
01:19:10.870 --> 01:19:14.300
Arise forth from the couchof lasting night,

1368
01:19:14.300 --> 01:19:17.170
Thou hate and terror toprosperity,

1369
01:19:17.170 --> 01:19:20.000
And I will kiss thydetestable bones

1370
01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:22.800
And put my eyeballs in thyvaulty brows

1371
01:19:22.800 --> 01:19:26.430
And ring my fingerswith thy household worms

1372
01:19:26.430 --> 01:19:31.530
And be a carrion monsterlike thyself:

1373
01:19:33.430 --> 01:19:36.730
Come, grin on me, and Iwill think thou smilest

1374
01:19:36.730 --> 01:19:41.130
And buss thee as thy wife.Misery's love,

1375
01:19:41.130 --> 01:19:42.930
O, come to me!

1376
01:19:42.930 --> 01:19:44.100
O fair affliction, peace!

1377
01:19:44.100 --> 01:19:47.530
No, no, I will not, havingbreath to cry:

1378
01:19:47.530 --> 01:19:49.700
O, that my tongue were inthe thunder's mouth!

1379
01:19:49.700 --> 01:19:53.270
Then with a passion wouldI shake the world;

1380
01:19:53.270 --> 01:19:55.400
And rouse from sleep thatfell anatomy

1381
01:19:55.400 --> 01:19:58.270
That cannot hear a lady'sfeeble voice,

1382
01:19:58.270 --> 01:20:01.430
Which scorns a moderninvocation.

1383
01:20:01.430 --> 01:20:04.770
Lady, you utter madness,and not sorrow.

1384
01:20:07.100 --> 01:20:10.630
Thou art not holy to belieme so;

1385
01:20:10.630 --> 01:20:16.230
I am not mad: this hair Itear is mine;

1386
01:20:16.230 --> 01:20:18.370
My name is Constance; Iwas Geffrey's wife;

1387
01:20:18.370 --> 01:20:23.270
Young Arthur is my son,and he is lost:

1388
01:20:24.500 --> 01:20:29.830
I am not mad: I would toheaven I were!

1389
01:20:30.670 --> 01:20:34.370
For then, 'tis like Icould forget myself:

1390
01:20:34.370 --> 01:20:38.730
O, if I could, what griefshould I forget!

1391
01:20:38.730 --> 01:20:42.200
Preach some philosophy tomake me mad,

1392
01:20:42.200 --> 01:20:46.270
And thou shalt becanonized, cardinal;

1393
01:20:46.270 --> 01:20:50.200
For being not mad butsensible of grief,

1394
01:20:50.200 --> 01:20:53.930
My reasonable partproduces reason

1395
01:20:53.930 --> 01:20:56.970
How I may be deliver'd ofthese woes,

1396
01:20:56.970 --> 01:21:02.330
And teaches me to kill orhang myself:

1397
01:21:02.330 --> 01:21:06.430
If I were mad, I shouldforget my son,

1398
01:21:06.430 --> 01:21:09.400
Or madly think a babe ofclouts were he:

1399
01:21:09.400 --> 01:21:14.730
I am not mad; too well,too well I feel

1400
01:21:14.730 --> 01:21:18.800
The different plague ofeach calamity.

1401
01:21:18.800 --> 01:21:22.270
Bind up those tresses. O,what love I note

1402
01:21:22.270 --> 01:21:25.500
In the fair multitude ofthose her hairs!

1403
01:21:25.500 --> 01:21:28.600
Where but by chance asilver drop hath fallen,

1404
01:21:28.600 --> 01:21:32.230
Even to that drop tenthousand wiry friends

1405
01:21:32.230 --> 01:21:34.630
Do glue themselves insociable grief,

1406
01:21:34.630 --> 01:21:38.970
Like true, inseparable,faithful loves,

1407
01:21:38.970 --> 01:21:40.930
Sticking together incalamity.

1408
01:21:40.930 --> 01:21:43.730
To England, if you will.

1409
01:21:43.730 --> 01:21:45.600
Bind up your hairs.

1410
01:21:45.600 --> 01:21:48.530
Aye, that I will; andwherefore will I do it?

1411
01:21:48.530 --> 01:21:51.630
I tore them from theirbonds and cried aloud

1412
01:21:51.630 --> 01:21:53.830
'O that these hands couldso redeem my son,

1413
01:21:53.830 --> 01:21:56.500
As they have given thesehairs their liberty!'

1414
01:21:56.500 --> 01:21:58.070
But now I envy at theirliberty,

1415
01:21:58.070 --> 01:22:00.900
And will again commit themto their bonds,

1416
01:22:00.900 --> 01:22:04.330
Because my poor boy is aprisoner.

1417
01:22:04.330 --> 01:22:08.930
And, father cardinal, Ihave heard you say

1418
01:22:08.930 --> 01:22:14.000
That we shall see and knowour friends in heaven:

1419
01:22:14.000 --> 01:22:17.800
If that be so, I shallsee my child again;

1420
01:22:17.800 --> 01:22:21.030
For since the birth ofCain, the first male child,

1421
01:22:21.030 --> 01:22:23.230
To him that did butyesterday suspire,

1422
01:22:23.230 --> 01:22:27.370
There was not such agracious creature born.

1423
01:22:27.370 --> 01:22:31.430
And now will canker-sorroweat my bud

1424
01:22:31.430 --> 01:22:35.630
And chase the nativebeauty from his cheek

1425
01:22:35.630 --> 01:22:40.200
And he will look as hollowas a ghost,

1426
01:22:40.200 --> 01:22:44.830
As dim and meagre as anague's fit,

1427
01:22:44.830 --> 01:22:51.200
And so he'll die; and,rising so again,

1428
01:22:51.200 --> 01:22:56.330
When I shall meet him atthe court of heaven

1429
01:22:56.330 --> 01:23:02.670
I shall not know him:therefore never, never

1430
01:23:02.670 --> 01:23:06.070
Must I behold my prettyArthur more.

1431
01:23:06.070 --> 01:23:10.870
You hold too heinous arespect of grief.

1432
01:23:10.870 --> 01:23:13.130
He talks to me that neverhad a son.

1433
01:23:13.130 --> 01:23:15.700
You are as fond of griefas of your child.

1434
01:23:20.170 --> 01:23:24.370
Grief fills the room up ofmy absent child,

1435
01:23:24.370 --> 01:23:29.000
Lies in his bed, walks upand down with me,

1436
01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:33.470
Puts on his pretty looks,repeats his ways,

1437
01:23:33.470 --> 01:23:38.930
Stuffs out his graciousgarments with his form;

1438
01:23:38.930 --> 01:23:42.030
Then, have I reason to befond of grief?

1439
01:23:44.730 --> 01:23:52.170
So fare you well: had yousuch a loss as I,

1440
01:23:52.170 --> 01:23:56.930
I could give bettercomfort than you have.

1441
01:23:56.930 --> 01:24:04.100
I will not keep this formupon my head,

1442
01:24:04.100 --> 01:24:10.800
When there is suchdisorder in my wit.

1443
01:24:10.800 --> 01:24:21.470
O Lord! my boy, my Arthur,my fair son!

1444
01:24:21.470 --> 01:24:29.100
My life, my joy, my food,my all the world!

1445
01:24:29.400 --> 01:24:36.470
My widow-comfort, and mysorrows' cure!

1446
01:24:38.500 --> 01:24:44.030
I fear some outrage, andI'll follow her.

1447
01:24:54.470 --> 01:24:57.370
There's nothing in thisworld can make me joy:

1448
01:25:02.870 --> 01:25:06.870
Life is as tedious as atwice-told tale

1449
01:25:06.870 --> 01:25:11.400
Vexing the dull ear of adrowsy man;

1450
01:25:11.400 --> 01:25:14.470
And bitter shame hath spoil'dthe sweet world's taste

1451
01:25:14.470 --> 01:25:19.100
That it yields nought butshame and bitterness.

1452
01:25:19.100 --> 01:25:23.770
Before the curing of astrong disease,

1453
01:25:23.770 --> 01:25:25.630
Even in the instant ofrepair and health,

1454
01:25:25.630 --> 01:25:29.530
The fit is strongest;evils that take leave,

1455
01:25:29.530 --> 01:25:35.630
On their departure most ofall show evil:

1456
01:25:35.630 --> 01:25:41.600
What have you lost bylosing of this day?

1457
01:25:41.600 --> 01:25:46.370
All days of glory, joy andhappiness.

1458
01:25:46.370 --> 01:25:49.500
If you had won it,certainly you had.

1459
01:25:51.570 --> 01:25:54.530
No, no; when Fortune meansto men most good,

1460
01:25:54.530 --> 01:25:58.000
She looks upon them with athreatening eye.

1461
01:25:58.000 --> 01:26:02.900
'Tis strange to think howmuch King John hath lost

1462
01:26:02.900 --> 01:26:07.570
In this which he accountsso clearly won:

1463
01:26:08.270 --> 01:26:11.230
Are not you grieved thatArthur is his prisoner?

1464
01:26:11.230 --> 01:26:13.830
As heartily as he is gladhe hath him.

1465
01:26:13.830 --> 01:26:19.000
Your mind is all asyouthful as your blood.

1466
01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:20.530
Now hear me speak with aprophetic spirit;

1467
01:26:20.530 --> 01:26:23.000
For even the breath ofwhat I mean to speak

1468
01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:27.970
Shall blow each dust, eachstraw, each little rub,

1469
01:26:27.970 --> 01:26:31.000
Out of the path thatshall directly lead

1470
01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:41.970
Thy foot to England'sthrone; and therefore mark.

1471
01:26:41.970 --> 01:26:45.170
John hath seized Arthur;and it cannot be

1472
01:26:45.170 --> 01:26:48.400
That, whiles warm life playsin that infant's veins,

1473
01:26:48.400 --> 01:26:51.470
The misplaced John shouldentertain an hour,

1474
01:26:51.470 --> 01:26:55.730
One minute, nay, one quietbreath of rest.

1475
01:26:55.730 --> 01:26:57.600
A sceptre snatch'd with anunruly hand

1476
01:26:57.600 --> 01:27:01.330
Must be as boisterouslymaintain'd as gain'd;

1477
01:27:01.330 --> 01:27:03.730
And he that stands upon aslippery place

1478
01:27:03.730 --> 01:27:08.900
Makes nice of no vile holdto stay him up:

1479
01:27:08.900 --> 01:27:15.130
That John may stand, thenArthur needs must fall;

1480
01:27:15.430 --> 01:27:20.430
So be it, for it cannot bebut so.

1481
01:27:20.430 --> 01:27:24.200
But what shall I gain byyoung Arthur's fall?

1482
01:27:24.200 --> 01:27:31.670
You, in the right of LadyBlanch your wife,

